==English==

===Etymology===
Probably from {{etyl|non|en}} {{m|non|slyngja}}, {{m|non|slyngva||to hurl}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*slingwaną||to worm, twist}} (compare Old English {{m|ang|slingan||to wind, twist}}, German {{m|de|schlingen||to swing, wind, twist}}, Danish {{m|da|slynge}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*slenk||to turn, twist}} (compare Welsh {{m|cy|llyngyr||worms, maggots}}, Lithuanian {{m|lt|sliñkti||to crawl like a snake}}, Latvian {{m|lv|slìkt||to sink}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈslɪŋ/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɪŋ|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|slings|slinging|slung|past2=slang|slung}}

# To [[throw]] with a circular or arcing motion.
#: {{rfquotek|Addison}}
# To throw with a sling.
#* Bible, Judges xx. 16
#*: Everyone could '''sling''' stones at an hairbreadth, and not miss.
# {{label|en|nautical}} To pass a rope around (a cask, gun, etc.) preparatory to attaching a hoisting or lowering [[tackle]].
# {{label|en|slang}} to [[sell]] [[drugs]]
#* '''2008''', Breaking Bad, Season 1, Episode 6:
#*: ''You may know a lot about chemistry man but you don't know jack about '''slinging''' dope''.

